pport of a war based on the justifications for it and the likelihood it will succeed, along with the costs that have been suffered in casualties. Of these factors, the book finds that the most important consideration for the public is the expectation of success. If the public believes that a mission will succeed, the public will support it even if the costs are high. When the public does not expect the mission to succeed, even small costs will cause the withdrawal of support. Providing a wealth of new evidence about American attitudes toward military conflict, Paying the Human Costs of War offers insights into a controversial, timely, and ongoing national discussion.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aIraq War, 2003-2011xPublic opinion. 0aPublic opinionxUnited States. 0aPublic opinionzUnited States. 0aWar and societyxUnited States. 0aWar and societyzUnited States. 0aWar casualtiesxPublic opinionxUnited States. 0aWar casualtieszUnited StatesxPublic opinion. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / International Relations / General.2bisacsh1 aFeaver, Peter D., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aReifler, Jason, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044250240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978140083009140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781400830091423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781400830091.jpg  a978-3-11-044250-2  Princeton University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK